{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476657"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13805"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13805"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.3,0.03,0.02,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55221"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6422"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40739"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"818"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16820"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18601"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43442"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55221"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of cough and fever. His parents report he has been breathing faster than usual and seems less active. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He attends daycare and his immunisations are up to date. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly distressed with a respiratory rate of 40/min, pulse rate 120/min, temperature 38.2\u00b0C, and oxygen saturation 94% on room air. Chest auscultation reveals decreased breath sounds in the right lower zone. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis based on the chest X-ray findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laryngotracheobronchitis","Right middle lobe collapse","Pleural effusion","Pneumothorax","Right lower lobe consolidation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray in this case shows \u003Cstrong\u003Eright middle lobe collapse\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a common finding in young children. The radiographic signs include loss of volume in the right middle lobe, seen as a wedge-shaped opacity extending from the right hilum towards the right lateral chest wall, and an upward shift of the horizontal fissure. The horizontal fissure, which normally separates the upper and middle lobes, appears more horizontal or even upward-sloping in middle lobe collapse. This condition is often caused by mucus plugging, which can result from viral infections or asthma. Right middle lobe consolidation would show no change in the horizontal fissure position. Thus the loss of volume and shift of the horizontal fissure are more indicative of collapse than consolidation in this case. The image provided shows where the opacity is, and the right heart border is unable to be seen, indicated with a red line.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaryngotracheobronchitis\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as croup, is a viral infection of the upper airway that typically presents with a characteristic barking cough, inspiratory stridor, and hoarseness. While it can cause respiratory distress, the chest X-ray findings in croup are usually normal or may show subglottic narrowing (steeple sign) on a lateral neck X-ray. The chest X-ray findings described in this case, with a wedge-shaped opacity in the right lung field, are not consistent with laryngotracheobronchitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a homogeneous opacity that obscures the costophrenic angle and may have a meniscus sign, typically visible at the lateral chest wall on an upright film. These features are not present in the provided image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E would be visible as a lucency without lung markings at the periphery of the lung, often with visible visceral pleural line. These findings are not present in this X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight lower lobe consolidation\u003C/strong\u003E would typically show a dense opacity in the right lower zone of the lung, often obscuring the right hemidiaphragm. On a frontal chest X-ray, this would appear as an opacity in the right lower lung field, extending from the right hilum inferiorly and laterally. The right heart border would typically remain visible. The X-ray findings described are more consistent with right middle lobe involvement rather than the lower lobe, as the opacity extends towards the right lateral chest wall at the level of the horizontal fissure, which is characteristic of middle lobe pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Right middle lobe collapse in children is often due to mucus plugging, which can be caused by viral infections or asthma.","Chest X-ray findings of right middle lobe collapse include loss of volume in the right middle lobe and shift of the horizontal fissure.","Persistent right middle lobe collapse may require bronchoscopy to exclude foreign body aspiration or anatomical abnormalities."],"references":["Right middle lobe collapse. In: Radiopaedia [online]. 2024; Retrieved 2024 Jun 28. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/right-middle-lobe-collapse","Shhada E, Nahle AA, Hamdar H, Jlailati A, Jawad A, Nahle Z, Ali S. Unveiling the complexity of right middle lobe syndrome: a case series highlighting the association with asthma. Ann Med Surg (Lond). 2024 Feb 19;86(4):1836-1842. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10990357/","Daltro P, Santos EN, Gasparetto TD, Ucar ME, Marchiori E. Pulmonary infections. Pediatr Radiol. 2011 May;41 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S69-82. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7079857/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40739"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13805"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20748"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21087"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20748"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vGcqQq3GOXgfRgxmzHD8YhOT3vIO1U.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vGcqQq3GOXgfRgxmzHD8YhOT3vIO1U.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":780,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"21087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21087"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tK0q88yajg3v5mNGC50lUJgAq4wxkJ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tK0q88yajg3v5mNGC50lUJgAq4wxkJ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":780,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40739"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T12:01:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-07T06:52:57+10:30"},"relationships":